## 10. Visual identity — typography unification with Mindmaker

### Keep distinct color palette, unify typography

**Rationale:** Krish's answer on visual identity was "unify with Mindmaker." But fully copying Mindmaker's mint + ink palette makes krishraja.com look like a subpage of Mindmaker rather than the author's identity. The right move is **same typography, overlapping-but-distinct colors**.

### Typography — CHANGE

Adopt Mindmaker's type stack:
- **Display font:** Space Grotesk Variable (for H1, H2 headlines)
- **Body font:** Inter Variable

Remove Georgia serif from the Hero greeting. Replace with Space Grotesk Italic at the same size.

Add to `index.html` preloads:
```html
<link rel="preload" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@100..900&family=Space+Grotesk:wght@300..700&display=swap" as="style" />
```

Update `tailwind.config.ts` font family tokens to match Mindmaker's.

### Color — EVOLVE, NOT REPLACE

Keep the confident blue identity but shift to a more editorial tone:

| Token | Current | New |
|---|---|---|
| Primary | `#0066FF` (saturated SaaS blue) | `#0055DD` (deeper, more editorial) |
| Primary-foreground | white | white |
| Background (light mode) | white/off-white | unchanged |
| Background (dark mode) | dark gray | `#0e1a2b` (Ink — matches Mindmaker) |
| Accent | none | `#7ef4c2` (Mint — used sparingly for link hovers and active states only) |

**Critical rule (mirrors Mindmaker):** never use mint on white/light backgrounds. Mint appears only on dark-mode sections as accent, never as primary.

### Why this works

- **Shared typography** signals "same author, same voice" across properties
- **Blue identity** preserves the personal brand distinct from Mindmaker
- **Shared ink + mint accent on dark** creates visual rhyme when someone moves between the two sites
- **Removes Georgia serif** which was the most dated element on the current site

### Theme color metadata update

Update `index.html`:
